 Trois femmes -- tSade, Revolution, and the Boundaries of Freedom -- tImpossible Crossings: Friedrich Hölderlin’s Hyperion and the Aesthetic Foundation of Democracy -- tÉvénements de circonstance: The Classical Tradition in the Age of Revolution -- tDetours of Knowledge: Aspects of Novalis’ Aesthetic Epistemology -- tChallenging Time(s): Memory, Politics, and the Philosophy of Time in Jean Paul’s Quintus Fixlein -- tXavier de Maistre and Angelology -- tIntroducing the Songs with Inspiration: William Blake, Lavater, and the Legacy of Felix Hess -- tThe Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in this volume discuss the overlap between philosophical, aesthetic, and political concerns in the 1790s either in the work of individuals or in the transfer of cultural materials across national borders, which tended to entail adaptation and transformation. What emerges is a clearer understanding of the “fate” of the Enlightenment, its radicalization and its “overcoming” in aesthetic and political terms, and of the way in which political “paranoia”, generated by the fear of a spreading revolutionary radicalism, facilitated and influenced the cultural transfer of the “radical”. The collection will be of interest to scholars in French, German, English, and comparative studies working on the later 18th century or early 19th century. It is of particular interest to those working on the impact of the French Revolution, those engaged in reception studies, and those researching the interface between political and cultural activites. It is also of key interest to intellectual historians of this period, as well as general historians with an interest in modern conservatism and radicalism.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0